Conceptual part¶

A.1.¶

Correct answer: ii. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, college graduates earn more, on average, than high school graduates.

Reason: There are no further information about how the interactions (i.e. $X4$ and $X5$) does look like. So I have to assume something:

Looking at question 3 I assume $X4=\frac{X1}{X2}$. Since $X3 \in [0,1]$, I would not assume $X5=\frac{X1}{X3}$, because this could end in an devision by zero. Therefore I assume it the other way around, i.e. $X5=\frac{X3}{X1}$, (assuming that there is no data with a GPA < 2.0, because otherwise they would have been no graduates).

Since GPA (X1) and IQ (X2) are fixed, X4 is also fixed. So the statement depends on X3 and X5, which means that we have show that there is a minimal value for $X1 \geq 2.0$ so that the part of the estimatied function containing the relevant predictors in our case, i.e. X3 and X5, is greater than 0: $$ \hat{\beta}_3*X3 + \hat{\beta}_5\frac{X3}{X1} > 0 \text{ | insert slopes and predictors} \\ 35*1-10\frac{1}{X1} > 0 \text{ | } +\frac{10}{X1} \\ 35 > \frac{10}{X1} \text{ | } * X1 \\ 35X1 > 10 \text{ | } / 35 \\ X1 > \frac{10}{35} $$ So the minimal value for the GPA would be $\frac{10}{35}=0.29$. But considering the domain here, it is impossible to graduate with a GPA < 2.0. So a college graduate is estimated to earn more than a high school graduate either way. (based on my assumptions above)

A.2.¶

$$ \hat{y} = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1X1 + \hat{\beta}_2X2 + \hat{\beta}_3X3 + \hat{\beta}_4X4 + \hat{\beta}_5X5 \text{ | insert estimated interception and slope} \\ \hat{y} = 50 + 20X1 + 0.07X2 + 35X3 + 0.01X4 + (-10)X5 \text{ | insert predictor values, with } X4=\frac{X1}{X2} \text{ and } X5=\frac{X3}{X1} \\ \hat{y} = 50 + 20*4.0 + 0.07*110 + 35*1 + 0.01*\frac{4.0}{110} -10 *\frac{1}{4.0} \text{ | calculate} \\ \hat{y} = 170.204 $$ So the predicted salary for the given predictors is 170204$ (based on my assumptions from A.1.).

A.3.¶

False: The (regression) coefficient was estimated for the estimation of a function that estimates the salary based on specific data. It does not tell anything about the interaction/correlation between the predictors used in this estimation, even if it is very small. If we want to find evidence for the interaction between two predictors, we need to consider the correletion coefficient of the two predictors (i.e. GPA and IQ). Even a look at the t-statistic and the p-value would give only information about the dependency between the interaction of the predictors itself and the estimated outcome of the estimates function, but not about the interaction between theses predictors.

I: Obtain a confidence interval for the coefficient estimates for the individual models.

This was aldready done by the code I used above. So I go right to the interpretation...

I: Interprete the results

Predictor: crim

The confidence intervall ranges from 23.229 to 24.837 for the intercept and from -0.501 to -0.329 for the slope. So we can assume (even assuming a normal distribution, which is the best we can do - anyway the central limit theorem kicks in here, since there are more than 30 datapoint) that the estimated linear function giving medv based on the single predictor (here crim) is likely to be: $\hat{f}(crim) = m*crim + n$, with $n \in [23.229,24.837]$ and $m \in [-0.501, -0.329]$. And this holds for 95% of all possible data.

Predictor: zn

The confidence intervall ranges from 20.083 to 21.752 for the intercept and from 0.110 to 0.174 for the slope. So we can assume (even assuming a normal distribution, which is the best we can do - anyway the central limit theorem kicks in here, since there are more than 30 datapoint) that the estimated linear function giving medv based on the single predictor (here zn) is likely to be: $\hat{f}(zn) = m*zn + n$, with $n \in [20.083,21.752]$ and $m \in [0.110, 0.174]$. And this holds for 95% of all possible data.

Predictor: indus

The confidence intervall ranges from 28.412 to 31.098 for the intercept and from -0.751 to -0.546 for the slope. So we can assume (even assuming a normal distribution, which is the best we can do - anyway the central limit theorem kicks in here, since there are more than 30 datapoint) that the estimated linear function giving medv based on the single predictor (here indus) is likely to be: $\hat{f}(indus) = m*indus + n$, with $n \in [28.412,31.098]$ and $m \in [-0.751, -0.546]$. And this holds for 95% of all possible data.

for feature in df.columns[df.columns != 'medv'].values[0:3]:
    print(f'FEATURE: {feature}')
    X = pandas.DataFrame({'intercept':np.ones(df.shape[0]),
                          feature:df[feature]})
    y = df['medv']
    lm = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    pred = lm.get_prediction(pandas.DataFrame({'intercept':np.ones(3),
                                               feature :[0,5,10] }))
    confi = pred.conf_int(obs=False, alpha=0.05)
    print(f'Confidence-Intervalls:')
    print(f'fit\t\t\tlow\t\t\thigh')
    for v_idx in range(len(pred.predicted_mean)):
        print(f'{pred.predicted_mean[v_idx]}\t{confi[v_idx][0]}\t{confi[v_idx][1]}')    
    
    predi = pred.conf_int(obs=True, alpha=0.05)
    print(f'Prediction-Intervalls:')
    print(f'fit\t\t\tlow\t\t\thigh')
    for v_idx in range(len(pred.predicted_mean)):
        print(f'{pred.predicted_mean[v_idx]}\t{predi[v_idx][0]}\t{predi[v_idx][1]}')    
    print('\n')

I: Interprete the results

There is just one predictor that shows a weak correleation to all the other predictors in general, i.e. chas.

The predictors rad and tax show a very strong positive correlation (0.91). The predictors that might be irrelevant for the multilinear model, i.e. age and indus, are strong positive correlated (0.73 and 0.76) to the nox predictor. Additionally they are strong negatively (-0.71 and -0.75) correlated to the dis predictor. This also hold for the nox predictor (-0.77). Maybe the irrelevance of indus and age in the fitted multilinear model is based on that correlations.

Just to mention one other (last) intereston correleations: The black parameter is mostlx negatively correlated to all of the other predictors (except dis).

from itertools import product

lstat_values = [5,10,15]
rm_values = [5,6.5,8]

                                     'rm':[5,6.5,8]})

combis = list(product(lstat_values, rm_values))

pred_values = pandas.DataFrame(combis, columns=['lstat', 'rm'])
